(35, 'en', 'S. M. Abdus Sattar ', 'Jessore', '21th June 1954', '2785', ' 0403010904', '0405010083', 'Sector 8', 'Muktibahinee', 'M. A. Manjur', '<p>S. M. Abdus Sattar was born in a religious Muslim family 22<sup>th</sup> November 1954 in a village Chatiyantola which situated at Churamonkathi upzilla in Jessore Sadaor,Jessore. He has two children. In the Liberation war he fought in sector 8 with bravery. His Gadget number: 2785, War ID Number: 0403010904, Muktibarta Number: 0405010083, Indian List No: 47413 and Ministry certificate Number: M-129458.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Here some information about him.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>Identities:</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p>S. M. Abdus Sattar, Father&rsquo;s name: Late Akkas Ali Sardar, Mother&rsquo;s name: Late Regia Khatun, Address: Chatiyantola, Churamonkathi,Jessore Sadar,Jessore. I fought in sector 8 in war. Sector commander&rsquo;s name was Major M A Manjur. Before I worked &nbsp;in Uttara Bank and then Akij Group, now retired. I have 2 sons.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>Participate in war and Operation:</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p>When the war began in 1971, I studied in Jessore M M College and was a first-year student of the college. Khitibdiya our neighboring villages on March 6 in the morning the war started, when the Pakistani army Jessore Cantonment and surrounding khitibdiya and shantala first entered the village and raided the village boys to torture the girl and poultry, all over cows and ghoat in a body 7th March speech of Bangabandhu, he more or less since we were ready to engage in battle janyeerai pursuant to which we had so we are waging war against the Pakistani army. And we have no heavy weapons, bullets, pistols or machine guns were not. Photos of our country as a weapon, khunta, was using the axe. When the war started, we did not realize it was understood that they attacked us, and we made a try to resist them. Consequently, over the course of 9 months with the start of the war of liberation and become.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>When they beat us on our sons and daughters, who were persecuted and even set fire to our homes would have burned everything, then we have parents, brothers and sisters, everyone would have gone to another village. The young-young boys in crowds crammed the war goes to India for training. The leaders of our freedom with the Government of India signed an agreement for training. So we all went to India, where we are going to take part in the war training. We are one of the first month capabariya bandya take part in the initial training. And then from there we were taken to the training periods of heavy weapons, light machine guns, and there we are, kuinch mortars, grenades, how culvert, bridges are burned. And that was our motto attacked fleeing the war there. We are faced with so many soldiers because we cannot fight. After 4 days of the British solitary base for the mortars kuinch Bihar training is done and there was a&nbsp; Utpal Sen, the Indian captain. We have a long 4-days training by the end of the cross border re-Chaugachha we crossed the river Ichamati saluya market, we GRP, sajiyali this area do. Because of our instruction on the Jessore Cantonment Cantonment, so why cannot the Pakistani side of the border regiments so Chaugachha to block the road. Our unit had a 11 and was commander of the unit&#39;s leader Altaf Hussain led to the collapse of the towers, we Chaugachha railcrossing next two full-length block is road. Khan came when he saw soldiers block the road. The block road would take 4-5 days to clear them. In this way, we are wasting their precious moment, we have tried to move forward. And there is a place that pairs the bridge is broken by the bear market saluya. The problem is many of them from one place to another place. Then there was a camp barinagar collaborators in high school we had to fight collaborators were forced to surrender.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>Reason of going to War:</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p>I went to the war prompted of patriotism. Since when do we know that education, Pakistani army on our parents, brothers and sisters all over the oppression, injustice, oppression, and torture. They also had higher priority jobs to their West Pakistani people, but in our case they&nbsp; &nbsp;were thinking evil eye Bengalis. Also in our country would have been jute prices. After all, they had deprived us from of all our rights. And our non-cooperation movement led by Bangabandhu, the 6-point movement was going on between us, when we were students, which was created in the context of a liberation we all crammed together against Pakistani troops are engaged in an active war.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>As a freedom&nbsp; fighter to a new generation demands:</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p>As a freedom that is available to a new generation demands, we have a lot of blood, mothers and sisters and lifelong made in exchange for the freedom of this country is that you want to leave and want to go with the responsibility to protect this freedom properly and learning in order to land and the pace of development is rich.</p>\r\n', '35.jpg', 'https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=CNnoMmEO6ok', 4, '1481216525', '2016-12-08'),
(36, 'en', 'MD. Abu Musa Gaze ', 'Jessore', '7th April 1953', '992', '0405010729', '0405010729', 'Sector 8', 'Muktibahinee', 'M. A. Manjur', '<p>MD. Abu Musa Gaze was born in Satiantala village in curamanakathi Union of Sadar Upazila of Jessore-7408 in respectable Muslim family in 7 April 1953. He is the father of 3 children. During the war, fought with great valour in Sector 8. His Gazette No. 992, War ID No. 0405010729 and the Ministry Certificate No. M - 90162. Some of the highlights of the conversation follow:</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>Identities:</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p>MD. Abu Musa Gaze, Father: late Noor Ali Gaze, Mother: Late Fatima Begum. &nbsp;Address: Satiantala, curamanakathi, Jessore Sadr, Jessore. I fought in Sector 8. The sector commander was Major M A Manzur. I was 16 years old on that time.&nbsp; I was in Army, I retired in 1986. I&rsquo;ve 2 sons and 1 daughter.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>Participation in the war and operation:</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; 30 March, 1971. That was Tuesday, hat day in Churamonkhati. Our Bengali army was in exercise. On that evening they were withdrawn and returned to the cantonment. I was in Churamonkhati market for shopping and I saw them. So we barricade on the road and all the people of market gathered on the road. We said that we wouldn&rsquo;t let them to enter. Then Bengali officers tried to understand us&rdquo; Look, we are government employee. We&rsquo;re not ordered yet to return, today we&rsquo;re ordered so we&rsquo;ve to go. &rdquo; Then they went away and I returned home. On that time I was in Monohorpur Colony. My father was in Army that time. When I was at bagdanga evening time had passed away. When I returned home my mother told me that my father didn&rsquo;t return. Then I came out to look for father. My mother advised me to go through Paltopara. When I came to my father I came to know that the person who supposed to do his duty, he was sick, so my father had to do the double duty. Mess Commander of there gave me dinner and a room to stay.&nbsp; Next morning they gave me tea, pure and fried vegetables. I said to my father,&rdquo; Father, Won&rsquo;t you go home&rdquo;? He answered in the positive. No sooner had I had finished, I saw the car of MP and Brigade commander. There was a fight in Quarter near to the Fare. We didn&rsquo;t see that live, we&rsquo;ve heard. After a while pistol firing was heard and everywhere firing was in rage. Then I ran to other side of the building and hide into a drain. During Pakistan period I had ansar training. So I know how to defence myself. There was a culvert near to the drain, so I went there. I saw that the first bangle forces were breaking the arsenal. I was thinking that should I run or not, if I ran I could be fired. So I didn&rsquo;t run. Still I was in that drain. I saw Sabed Ali Vuiya who was a Habilder named as my uncle. He was known to me. He was carrying 2 SMG and a bag full of shots. When he saw me, he asked me why I was here. I told him that I was stack. Then he told me to go with him. We pass the road by scrolling. Then he tried to observe, from which side most of the shots were coming standing behind a date tree beside the post office. It was not possible for us to fire from there. So we had to back off from there and took shelter into a dry pond. There was no way to escape from there. There was only firing sound all around. We didn&rsquo;t have any strength to stand. We stayed there as long the firing ended. Meanwhile in this time he taught me how to use weapon and load the magazine.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; There was no news of my father whether he was dead or alive. About 5 or 5.30 pm, firing put an end. Then we started to scroll inside the date tree and reached Paltopara. We didn&rsquo;t find anyone there. Some dead body were here and there. There was a drain through water runs to the Monohorpur Lake. Entering into the drain we moved forward slowly. I was holding rifle up because of water. There was a bridge at the end of the road. When we reached there we saw military truck inside the field. And some guys got Red Cross builder on their body. Backside of the truck was open and they were throwing something into the truck, whether that was dead body or not, we didn&rsquo;t understand. Frequently I told my uncle that it wouldn&rsquo;t be so safe to stay here as they would search at night. Uncle asked where to go. Subedar Mr Abdul Razzaq lived in Gobindopur. His real resident was in Comilla, Doudkandi. He was the no 14 prisoner of Agartola conspiracy. We decided to go there. We passed the lake from dry side. 4 more military mans joined with us. 2 of them had weapon. We went to Abdul Razzaq house and he listen everything. Meanwhile, where we lived in colony, my mother, brother, sister all left the place and I didn&rsquo;t know where they had gone. So Abdul Razzaq made some arrangement for us to stay and asked us what to do. We told that you and Vuiya uncle should discuss about this matter. He told us not to go there with weapons. It could be more dangerous. So we put down our weapons and came to the front lake through Chanditar. Crossing the lake we came to Baditola Mosque. Then we saw 4 military trucks were coming through Monohorpur market. Then they got down and started to move in a single line and came to the end of Monohorpur colony. &nbsp;Then they started firing and stopped until it was 11am. There was a banyan tree in Baditola. A mortar shell hit that tree and I got so frightened. Then we move zigzag and returned. After a discussion we understood that we couldn&rsquo;t stay here. We had to move on. We crossed maoa border by on foot. There was a high authority discussion took place and let us in. I fought in sector 8. My job was to clear border from 15 to 20 miles, so who were entered doesn&rsquo;t interrupt by anything. We were in main defence. The transit point of liberation fighters were in Kollan. From there, groups were divided and which group will enter from where is decided. Which groups were in our side, we had to cross them that area.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; On 10-10-1971, some of our Bengali mans escaped from Pakistan army. Meanwhile, there was a discussion with Indira Gandhi about our recognition. Pakistan wants to hold the country and we want to independent our country at any cost. That was our main motive. &nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>Reason for going to the Liberation War:</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; I went to the liberation war to liberate my motherland Bangladesh.&nbsp; WE heard the 7<sup>th</sup> March announcement on 8<sup>th</sup> March on radio. For which reason we fought, we didn&rsquo;t get the country like that way. Recovering and conducting a destroyed country is so tough.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>Expectation to the young generation:</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p>My Expectation to the young generation is, we independent our country by sacrificing a lot of lives.&nbsp; We brought this red and green flag and they should hang it up and learn the real thing about the war and let the next generation to know .So they should conduct Bangladesh in such a way that we can stand high in the world.</p>\r\n', '36.jpg', 'https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=e5uPECzz5so', 2, '1481216966', '2016-12-08');
